<h1>Viṣṇu Sahasranāma — Verse 14</h1>
<div class="subtitle">Complete Enumeration: All 80 Linguistically Valid Decompositions</div>

<div class="verse-block">
<div class="script-label">Devanāgarī</div>
<div>विश्वं विष्णुर् वषट्कारो भूतभव्यभवत्प्रभुः ।</div>
<div>भूतकृद् भूतभृद् भावो भूतात्मा भूतभावनः ॥</div>
<div class="script-label">Telugu</div>
<div>విశ్వం విష్ణుర్ వషట్కారో భూతభవ్యభవత్ప్రభుః |</div>
<div>భూతకృద్ భూతభృద్ భావో భూతాత్మా భూతభావనః ||</div>
<div class="script-label">IAST</div>
<div>viśvaṃ viṣṇur vaṣaṭkāro bhūtabhavyabhavatprabhuḥ |</div>
<div>bhūtakṛd bhūtabhṛd bhāvo bhūtātmā bhūtabhāvanaḥ ||</div>
</div>

<div class="discovery">
<h2>Summary</h2>
<p>88 characters of continuous Sanskrit. <strong>80</strong> linguistically valid decompositions.</p>
<p>Every segment is either an <span class="att">● attested name</span> (all traditions agree) or a <span class="cmp">◎ valid compound</span> (grammatically correct, doctrinally meaningful).</p>
<table class="summary-table">
<tr><th>Names</th><th>Readings</th><th>Character</th></tr>
<tr><td>3</td><td>1</td><td>Maximally monistic — all functions as one</td></tr>
<tr><td>4</td><td>7</td><td></td></tr>
<tr><td>5</td><td>19</td><td></td></tr>
<tr><td>6</td><td>26</td><td></td></tr>
<tr><td>7</td><td>19</td><td>Most ambiguity — the doctrinal sweet spot</td></tr>
<tr><td>8</td><td>7</td><td>Seven ways to merge exactly one pair</td></tr>
<tr><td>9</td><td>1</td><td>UNIQUE MAXIMUM — every possible split taken</td></tr>
</table>
</div>

